Blume.
</taxonomicName>
(Autumn maple tree)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="51" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,152,972]" pageId="2" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,311,740,764]" pageId="2" pageNumber="51">Remarks:</emphasis>
This new species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Sohi (1977)" authorityName="Sohi" authorityYear="1977" box="[620,905,741,764]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Plumosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="emarginata">
<emphasis box="[620,769,741,764]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="51">P. emarginata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Sohi, A. S." box="[776,905,741,764]" pageId="2" pageNumber="51" pagination="355 - 357" refId="ref1286" refString="Sohi, A. S. (1977) New genera and species of Typhlocybinae (Homoptera: Cicadellidae) from North-Westen India. Oriental Insects, 11 (3), 355 - 357." type="journal article" year="1977">Sohi (1977)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, sharing with the latter the similar crown, and the subgenital plate having a lamelliform process on the inner lateral surface subapically, numerous short microsetae basally along the lateral margin and long white fine setae at the apex. It can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sohi" authorityYear="1977" box="[1139,1288,810,833]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Plumosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="emarginata">
<emphasis box="[1139,1288,810,833]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="51">P. emarginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its unique aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[265,371,845,868]" captionStart="FIGURES 1-13" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[176,1407,183,1864]" captionTargetId="figure-77@1.[170,1417,181,1877]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1-13. Plumosa nigrimaculata n. sp. 1. Head and thorax, dorsal view. 2. Face. 3. Tip of abdomen, left lateral view. 4. Style. 5. Aedeagus, caudal view. 6. Aedeagus, lateral view. 7. Connective. 8. Abdominal apodemes. 9. Forewing. 10. Hindwing. 11. Pygofer lobe, lateral view. 12. Subgenital plate, inner-lateral view; P. emarginata Sohi, 1977: 13. Aedeagus, lateral view (after Sohi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5133704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5133704/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="51">Figs. 5, 6</figureCitation>
): aedeagal shaft with a short thin tooth on the dorsal margin and a pair of small ventral processes basally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="51" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,152,972]" pageId="2" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,330,914,938]" pageId="2" pageNumber="51">Etymology:</emphasis>
The name is derived from the Latin prefix “nigri-” (black, dark) plus “macula” (spot, mark), which refers to the large black patch on the scutellum apex (
<figureCitation box="[721,784,949,972]" captionStart="FIGURES 1-13" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[176,1407,183,1864]" captionTargetId="figure-77@1.[170,1417,181,1877]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1-13. Plumosa nigrimaculata n. sp. 1. Head and thorax, dorsal view. 2. Face. 3. Tip of abdomen, left lateral view. 4. Style. 5. Aedeagus, caudal view. 6. Aedeagus, lateral view. 7. Connective. 8. Abdominal apodemes. 9. Forewing. 10. Hindwing. 11. Pygofer lobe, lateral view. 12. Subgenital plate, inner-lateral view; P. emarginata Sohi, 1977: 13. Aedeagus, lateral view (after Sohi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5133704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5133704/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="51">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
